File: platform/shared/src/index.ts, lines 424-425. The condition `host !== '*'` on line 425 allows bare wildcard hosts through. A pattern like 'https://*/*' matches every HTTPS page — this is as broad as the already-rejected '*://*/*'. Fix: add a check after line 419 (after the bare TLD wildcard check) that rejects host === '*'. Something like:

if (host === '*') {
  return `URL pattern "${pattern}" is too broad — "*" matches all domains. Use a specific domain or wildcard subdomain (e.g., *.example.com)`;
}

Then remove `host !== '*' &&` from the validation condition on line 425 since it's now handled above.

Also update the test at platform/shared/src/validation.test.ts line 189 — the test currently asserts 'https://*/api' is valid. After this fix, it should be rejected. Add new test cases for 'https://*/*', 'http://*/*', and '*://*/path' to verify they are all rejected.

Note: The IP validation allowing octets > 255 (line 427) is a very low-severity issue — do not fix it in this story to keep the change focused.

File: platform/plugin-sdk/src/log.ts, lines 82-103 (safeSerializeArg function, JSON fallback branch). The JSON.stringify at line 85 has no size limit. After the JSON round-trip at line 100, check the stringified length. If it exceeds a limit (suggest MAX_SERIALIZED_SIZE = 65536 or 64 * 1024), return a truncated version. For example:

const json = JSON.stringify(value, replacer);
if (json.length > MAX_SERIALIZED_SIZE) {
  return json.slice(0, MAX_SERIALIZED_SIZE) + '...[truncated]';
}
return JSON.parse(json);

Actually, since the function returns `unknown` (parsed JSON), not a string, you need to handle this differently. The simplest approach: if json.length > MAX_SERIALIZED_SIZE, return the string `[Object truncated: ${json.length} chars]` instead of the parsed object. This avoids parsing a huge string just to truncate it.

Add test in platform/plugin-sdk/src/log.test.ts (create if needed, or find existing tests).
